### Abstract

The pharmacokinetics of the angiotensin II receptor antagonist {{ drug.name }} and its active carboxylic acid metabolite {{ drug.molecular_formula }} were characterized in 18 healthy male subjects after administration of {{ drug.route_of_administration }} losartan, {{ drug.route_of_administration }} {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, and {{ drug.route_of_administration }} losartan. In these subjects, the average plasma clearance of losartan was {{ drug.strength }}/min, and the volume of distribution was 34 L. Renal clearance ({{ drug.strength }}/min) accounted for 12% of plasma clearance. Terminal half‐life was 2.1 hours. In contrast, the average plasma clearance of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} was {{ drug.strength }}/min, and its volume of distribution was 10 L. Renal clearance was {{ drug.strength }}/min, which accounted for 55% of plasma clearance; terminal half‐life was 6.3 hours. After {{ drug.route_of_administration }} administration of losartan, peak concentrations of losartan were reached in 1 hour. Peak concentrations of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} were reached in 312 hours. The area under the plasma concentration‐time curve of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} was about four times that of losartan. The {{ drug.route_of_administration }} bioavailability of losartan {{ drug.dosage_form }} was 33%. The low bioavailability was mainly attributable to first‐pass metabolism. After {{ drug.route_of_administration }} or {{ drug.route_of_administration }} administration of losartan the conversion of losartan to the metabolite {{ drug.molecular_formula }} was 14%.

Clinical Pharmacology & Therapeutics (1995) 58, 641–649.
